prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: CO(2-1) in GAMA09 galaxies at z=0.43-0.8
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: The most efficient way to carry out a survey of CO emission from star-forming galaxies as a function of redshift is to fix the spectral ALMA setup at a frequency such that we maximise the number of galaxies with the CO line falling in the same spectral setup. This is the same approach we have done before with our successful Cycle1 and Cycle2 experiments. Is for this reason we have decided to manually set the observing frequencies, leaving the redshift entry at cero.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
The basebands have been setup manually so we maximise the number of galaxies with the CO(2-1) emission line falling in a single ~7.5GHz spectral coverage.
The typical CO line FWHMs of these galaxies are expected to be of the order of 150km/s. Spectral averaging of 16 channels obtaining ~15km/s resolution is higher than required for our science goals. Our noise estimate defined to detect the line is based on 65km/s channel widths, therefore we aim to average the data post delivery to gain signal-to-noise in the CO(2-1) line.

This survey is designed to detect galaxies between z~0.4-0.8. Almost all galaxies have sizes smaller than 5" on sky (<5% between 5" and 7"). Given that we are interested in global properties for these galaxies, we request point-like detections for almost all of them. Is for this reason we request a synthesised beam no smaller than 4". Please note this experiment could be executed with lower resolutions >4" as well.

Galaxies are selected from the Herschel-ATLAS survey, so all them got broad-band photometry at 100, 160, 250, 350 and 500um. Targets also got secure spectroscopic redshifts from the GAMA & SDSS surveys.
Using the redshifts and the Herschel photometry we can estimate the integrated IR luminosity (8-1000um). The SED is well characterised by a modified black body emission (T~24K, beta~1.8) truncated to a power-law (slope~2) in the mid-IR part of the SED.
We select galaxies at z~0.43-0.80 with infrared luminosities of L_IR~10^11-12Lo with their CO(2-1) line emission falling in a fixed ALMA spectral setup (minimising overheads -- see our manual baseband's centres).
Using the relation given by Solomon and Vanden Bout (2005): log(L_IR) = 1.7 x Log[L'_CO(1-0)] - 5.0
we are able to estimate the L'_CO(1-0) luminosity. Then we assume a typical ratio of L'_CO(2-1)/L'_CO(1-0) = 0.85
so we estimate the expected L'_CO(2-1)luminosity for all galaxies. Using now the relation given by Eqn.3 in Solomon & Vanden Bout (2005) L'_CO(2-1) = 3.25x10^7 x S_CO(2-1) x Delta_V * nu_obs^-2 * D_L^2 x (1+z)^-3
we are able to estimate the velocity-integrated flux (S_CO(2-1) x Delta_V) for the CO(2-1) emission line.
Considering a typical width of 150km/s for the line (similar to our previous CO(1-0) findings in previous ALMA experiments) we estimate the peak_CO values observed in channels of 65km/s width, finding that they scatter all over between 4 and 15mJy (6mJy median).
Considering that we would like to detect an unresolved peak CO line for almost all galaxies at >5-sigma significance (point-like), we request a rms of 1mJy at 65km/s channel widths.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We request 5.5 hrs of ALMA time in Band-4 to observe 68 point-like galaxies at 0.43<z<0.7 targeting the CO(2-1) transition line as a tracer of the molecular gas content. Our sample is selected from the Herschel Astrophysical Terahertz Large Area Survey and provides a unique opportunity put these far-IR emitters in the cosmological context of galaxy evolution. The spectroscopic ALMA setup has been perfectly adjusted to maximise the number of galaxies which are capable to observe in three well defined science goals providing wide redshift coverage. These observations will help us to identify galaxies with high content of molecular gas, with similar properties to those found at high-z. Based on our previous related ALMA observations we will spatially resolve some of the galaxies allowing an estimate of the Kennicut-Schmidt law, while on the other hand most of the galaxies will be spectroscopically resolved so we will be able to check if the Tully-Fisher relation changes at these redshifts. This proposal is a natural extension up to z=0.7 of our previous programs using band-3 targeting similar galaxies, and it will be a key part of the PhD thesis of the P.I. V. Villanueva.
